China Steel, ICBC, PetroChina: Asia Ex-Japan Equity Preview

-- B y   A n u c h i t   N g u y e n
-- 
2011-08-25T21:55:48Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-08-25/china-steel-icbc-petrochina-asia-ex-japan-equity-preview.html
The following companies may have
unusual price changes today in Asian trading, excluding  Japan .
Stock symbols are in parentheses and share prices are from the
previous close, unless noted otherwise.  China Steel Corp. (2002)  (2002 TT):  Taiwan ’s largest producer will
raise prices of some products after demand from car and
machinery makers rose and costs climbed. Prices will increase by
an average 1 percent for October and November contracts with
domestic customers, the Kaohsiung-based company said in an e-
mailed statement. Hot-rolled coil, a benchmark product, will
rise by an average NT$489 ($17) a metric ton, the company said.
The shares were unchanged at NT$29.50.  Cebu Air Inc. (CEB)  : The Philippine budget carrier says
it is now the largest airline operating to, from and within the
country with 258,120 seat capacity, a stock-exchange filing
showed. The company said it will take delivery of four Airbus
A320 aircraft in the last four months of the year. The stock
increased 3.1 percent to 80.70 pesos.  Hyundai Heavy Industries Co. (009540 KS): Orders in the
first seven months of this year rose 70 percent from a year
earlier to $19.1 billion, Hyundai Heavy said in a regulatory
filing. Sales in July climbed 14 percent to 1.88 trillion won,
it said. The shares climbed 3.3 percent to 313,500 won.  Industrial & Commercial Bank of China (601398)  Ltd. (1398 HK): The
world’s largest lender by market value said first-half profit
jumped 29 percent to a record on higher loans and fees in the
world’s fastest-growing major economy. Net income rose to 109.5
billion yuan ($17 billion), or 0.31 yuan a share, from 84.6
billion yuan, or 0.25 yuan, a year earlier, the Beijing-based
lender said in a statement to the Hong Kong stock exchange. The
stock added 1.9 percent to HK$4.85.  LG Chem Ltd. (051910)  (051910 KS):  South Korea ’s biggest chemicals
maker will jointly build a $4 billion plant in  Kazakhstan  with
state-run Kazakhstan Petrochemical Industries, aiming to tap
cheaper raw materials. The partners will have equal stakes in
the project, to be located in Atyrau, Seoul-based LG Chem said
in a statement after signing a contract in Astana with the
Kazakh company. The plant will have an annual capacity of
840,000 metric tons of ethylene and 800,000 tons of polyethylene
and begin commercial production in 2016. LG Chem gained 1.8
percent to 347,500 won.  PAL Holdings Inc. (PAL)  : Philippine Airlines Inc., a
unit of the company, will take delivery of eight aircraft from
next year until 2013, Philippine Airlines President Jaime
Bautista. The airline may revise its “modest profit outlook”
in the current fiscal year given higher oil prices and profit in
the second quarter may not be as “good as last year,” he said.
The stock fell 4.3 percent to 6.03 pesos.  PetroChina Co. (857 HK):  Asia ’s biggest company by market
value posted a first-half profit that missed analysts’ estimates
after increases in state-controlled fuel prices lagged behind
gains in crude oil costs. Net income climbed 1 percent to 66
billion yuan ($10.3 billion), or 0.36 yuan per share, from 65.3
billion yuan, or 0.36 yuan, a year earlier, the Beijing-based
energy explorer and oil refiner said in a Hong Kong stock
exchange filing. That compares with the 67.3 billion-yuan median
estimate of six analysts surveyed by Bloomberg. PetroChina
increased 1.8 percent to HK$9.51.  Samsung Electronics Co. (005930 KS): Samsung won’t acquire
Hewlett-Packard Co.’s PC business, the South Korean company’s
chief executive officer, Choi Gee Sung, said in an e-mailed
statement. Samsung rose 2.4 percent to 725,000 won.  To contact the reporter on this story:
